<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-789-661  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 789 661.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Engineering  Dec 1990 v9 n12 p56(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Peripherals: CAD systems rely on a slew of add-on hardware.andO;(computer-aided design)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mills, Robert; Carrabine, Laura.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A variety of add-on computerized hardware facilitates thecomputer-aided design (CAD) process.andP;  These devices arecategorized as data entry hardware, hardcopy output units,specialized graphics equipment and memory.andP;  Data entry productsused in CAD include mice, digitizers and tablets and scanners.andO;Hardcopy output products provide either vector or raster output.andO;Vector output devices include pen plotters.andP;  Raster output devicesinclude laser, electrostatic, direct imaging, dot matrix, thermaltransfer and ink jet printers.andP;  Specialized graphics hardware forCAD include graphics monitors and graphics processor-based boardsfor microcomputers.andP;  Memory products for CAD systems includememory chips and such mass storage devices as floppy disk drives,hard-disk drives, removable hard disks, optical disks and tapecartridge units for backup.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided DesignAdd-In/On DevicesMicePlottersGraphics SystemsMass MemoryDigitizersScanning DevicesPrinters.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>